57–10 September 1461","1357–1461":"1357–1461","1350–1432":"1350–1432","1357–1426":"1357–1426","1379–1461":"1379–1461","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1297–Female":"1297–Deceased","1297":"1297","13 January 1426":"13 January 1426","10 Sep 1461":"10 September 1461","1340":"1340","1461":"1461","1350":"1350","10 September 1461":"10 September 1461","Abt 1340":"about 1340","1426":"1426","1357":"1357","1379":"1379","1432":"1432","1376":"1376","Elton, Cheshire, England":"Elton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Pomeroy, Devonshire, England, UK":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Berry Pomeroy, Devonshire, England, UK":"Berry Pomeroy, Devon, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Woolstone Manor, Bude, Cornwall, England":"Woolstone, Berkshire, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Collaton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire) and Irish: variant of   Colliton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Colliton","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Haldan</b>, see   Caldon  .","English: habitational name from any of several places in Devon variously called Colliton, Colyton, or Collaton. Colliton and Collaton are named with the Old English personal name <i>Cola</i> (see   Cole   2) + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’; Colyton is ‘settlement on the Coly river’, a Celtic river name. Both these names are now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret De Collaton 1 W